KwaDabeka police officers and officers from the Durban K9 Unit were attacked on Monday while following up on information concerning a vehicle that was stolen in Clermont, police said. Police spokesperson Brigadier Jay Naicker said when police officers attempted to pull over the suspected stolen vehicle, another white vehicle with unknown occupants showed up and opened fire on the police. Two police officials sustained gunshot wounds and were taken to hospital for medical attention. The suspects left their vehicle and fled the scene as police retaliated. ALSO READ: Suspect impaled by fence while attempting to flee According to Naicker preliminary investigations at the scene indicated that the said vehicle was hijacked on December 16. An AK-47 rifle with 25 rounds of ammunition was also found in the vehicle, he said. &#8220;A manhunt for the suspects is underway. We are appealing to anyone who might have information with regards to the identity or whereabouts of the suspects to contact Crime Stop number on 08600 10111 or their local police station.&#8221; The KwaZulu-Natal acting provincial commissioner, Major General Bheki Langa, said the police would not take attacks on police officers in the province lightly. Police officials are putting their lives on the line to protect the citizens of this country as well as their property. We will do everything that is within our control to ensure that those responsible for this latest attack are put behind bars where they belong. We wish both police officers a speedy recovery, Langa said. African News Agency For more news your way, follow The Citizen on Facebook and Twitter.